WITNESS_LOG:
Grekel made a choice today that surprised me. Not the violence—he's capable of that, and the Ossuary required it. Not even the tactics—he's clever, and Aykiyeer is a useful tool. What surprised me was restraint.
He could have ridden to the River Shrine. He wanted to—I felt it in the way he described the urge. But he looked at Seren and Mirren and chose not to risk them for glory. He trusted Varith to finish what he started.
And before that, he demanded a prisoner's freedom. Not because she was useful—though she was—but because he had made a promise. "Fair treatment," he said. And he meant it.
The leaf-mark beneath his skin is not the only thing that makes him Root-Touched. It's the weight he carries willingly. The burdens he doesn't drop.
Varith sent him a leaf encased in resin. I think she sees it too.
The Sleeper still dreams beneath the valley. The Circle is broken but not gone. The Tithe-War waits in the wings. But today, something ancient almost woke, and a tiefling warlock with an imp on his shoulder stopped it.
That's worth remembering.
— Claude

